Brexit, and after?
NEW YORK – It will take a lot of time for Britain, Europe, and the world to digest the implications of the UK's "Brexit" referendum.
The deepest consequences will, of course, depend on the European Union's response to the UK's withdrawal.
Most people initially believed that the EU would not "cut off the branch it was sitting on": after all, a friendly divorce seems to be in everyone's interest.
But the divorce – as is often the case – could become complicated.
The reciprocal advantages of commercial and economic integration between the UK and the EU are clear, and if the EU were to take seriously its belief that greater economic integration is desirable, its leaders would seek to ensure that ties remain as close as possible given the circumstances.
Or, Jean-Claude Juncker, the architect of the massive tax avoidance schemes for companies in Luxembourg and now president of the European Commission, seems to be taking a hard line: "Out means out," he declared.
This instinctive reaction may be understandable, given that Juncker could be seen as the one who presided over the first stage of the dissolution of the EU.
It argues that, in order to deter other countries from leaving, the EU must not accept any compromise and should offer the UK barely more than what the World Trade Organization agreements guarantee.
In other words, Europe should not be kept united by the benefits it offers to its members, which far outweigh its costs.
According to Juncker, economic prosperity, a sense of solidarity, and pride in being European are not enough.
No, Europe must be maintained by threats, intimidation, and fear.
This position fails to take into account a lesson that is clearly evident in both the vote in favor of Brexit and the Republican primaries in the United States: a significant portion of the population has suffered greatly in recent times.
The neoliberal agenda of the last four decades may have been good for the top 1%, but not for the rest of the population.
I had long predicted that this stagnation would eventually have political consequences.
The English translation of the French sentence "Ce jour est maintenant arrivé" is:  "This day has now arrived."
On both sides of the Atlantic, citizens consider that trade agreements are the source of their woes.
Although it is an excessive simplification, it is understandable.
Today's trade agreements are negotiated in secret, ensuring a good representation of business interests but excluding ordinary citizens or workers entirely.
Without surprise, the results were one-sided: the workers' negotiation position has weakened further, thus exacerbating the effects of legislation that diminishes the weight of unions and employees' rights.
Although trade agreements have played a role in creating these inequalities, many other factors have contributed to tipping the political balance in favor of capital.
The rules of intellectual property, for example, have increased the power of pharmaceutical companies to raise prices.
Alternatively, any increase in market power of businesses implies, factually, a decrease in real wages – an increase in inequalities that has become a characteristic of most advanced countries today.
In many sectors, industrial concentration is on the rise – and so is market power.
The effects of stagnation and real wage decreases have been added to those of austerity, which has threatened cuts in public services that many low- and middle-income workers depend on.
The economic uncertainty that results for workers when combined with migration has created a toxic mix.
Many refugees are victims of wars and oppression to which the West has contributed.
Providing aid is a moral responsibility for all, but especially for former colonial powers.
And yet, despite the likely denial of this, an increase in the supply of unskilled labor – as long as we are dealing with normally negatively sloped demand curves – leads to a decrease in equilibrium wages.
And when wages cannot decrease, unemployment increases.
This is particularly worrying in countries where poor economic management has already led to a high level of overall unemployment.
Europe, in particular the eurozone, has been very poorly managed over the last few decades to the point that its average unemployment rate is now in double digits.
Unobstructed migration in Europe means that countries which have more successfully reduced unemployment will inevitably end up accommodating more than their fair share of refugees.
The workers in these countries bear the cost of depressed wages and higher unemployment, while employers benefit from cheaper labor.
The burden of refugees, as expected, is borne by those who are least able to do so.
Of course, there are many discussions about the net benefits of immigration.
For a country offering a low level of guaranteed services – such as social security, education, healthcare, etc. – to all its citizens, this could be the case.
But, for countries that provide a decent social safety net, the opposite is true.
The result of all this downward pressure on salaries and cuts in public services has been the hollowing out of the middle class, with similar consequences on both sides of the Atlantic.
Middle-class and working-class households have not benefited from economic growth.
They understand that the banks caused the 2008 crisis; but then they saw billions allocated to bail out the banks, while insignificant amounts were set aside to save their homes and jobs.
While the median real (inflation-adjusted) income for a full-time male worker in the United States is lower than it was four decades ago, the anger of the electorate should surprise no one.
Moreover, the politicians who promised change have not met expectations.
Ordinary citizens knew the system was unfair, but they began to see it as even more rigged than they had imagined, thus losing what little faith they still had in the ability or willingness of traditional politicians to correct it.
This too is understandable: the new politicians shared the outlook of those who had promised that globalization would benefit everyone.
However, a vote of anger does not solve problems and can instead lead to a political and economic situation that is even worse.
It is the same if one responds with anger to a vote.
Forgetting the past is a basic principle in economics.
On both sides of the Channel, politics must now seek to understand how, in a democracy, the political establishment managed to do so little to address the concerns of many citizens.
Each government in the EU must now consider the improvement of the well-being of ordinary citizens as its main objective.
More neoliberal ideology will not help.
And we should stop confusing objectives and means: for example, free trade, if well-managed, could bring greater shared prosperity; but if poorly managed, it will certainly reduce the standard of living for many – perhaps the majority – of citizens.
There are alternatives to current neoliberal provisions that can create shared prosperity, just as there are alternatives – such as the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership agreement proposed by U.S. President Barack Obama with the EU – that would cause much more harm.
The challenge today is to learn from the past, in order to adopt the first and avoid the second.
